Located on the airfield of the former RAF Llandwrog, the museum has an impressive collection of aircraft and aviation memorabilia. Vampire, along with the only T2 BAe Harrier remaining worldwide.

Part of the museum is devoted to the creation of the RAF Mountain Rescue Service, started here at RAF Llandwrog in 1942, whilst other sections describe the wartime airfields of North Wales

amphitheater-of-el-jem.description:
El Jem's Amphitheater and museum more than make up for the disappointment of Carthage, and it is well worth a special trip to see them.

The amphitheater is huge (3rd largest in the world), and at least has a little interpretation. You can climb all the way up to the highest levels and look down on the floor (and the town), and also explore the underground levels.

Honestly, it's better than the Roman Colosseum in many ways. Beautiful photography opportunities abound.

A 15 minute walk takes you to the museum, which is chock full of huge (room-sized) intact Roman mosaics. One of the best collections I've ever seen.

Worth at least an hour, two plus if you include the museum. A half day in El Jem is not out of order.

Wildly ambitious but never fully-built, designed as an 'arcology' - a dense space for living/working (hello "SimCity" fans).  The construction is from concrete panels that are cast in dirt and then tilted/lifted into position, but in much wilder shapes than modern tilt-wall buildings.

avebury-stone-circles.description:
Avebury henge and stone circles are one of the greatest marvels of prehistoric Britain. Built and much altered during the Neolithic period, roughly between 2850 BC and 2200 BC, the henge survives as a huge circular bank and ditch, encircling an area that includes part of Avebury village. Within the henge is the largest stone circle in Britain - originally of about 100 stones - which in turn encloses two smaller stone circles.

See https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/avebury/

It's also possible to walk around the site, but sadly the basins aren't that interesting to see and there's no interpretation.

canyon-de-chelly.description:
The various Canyon de Chelly overlooks are among the most beautiful vistas that this author has ever seen. A must-see if you're on Highway 191.

canyon-de-chelly.name: Canyon de Chelly

carthage-in-general.description:
The ruins of Carthage are generally a disappointment, even if you're a Roman history buff. For the most part, they're in poor condition and poorly curated/explained. The various ruins are also pretty spread out. Still walkable, but you end up spending a lot of time getting from one slightly disappointing ruin to another.

The Carthage Museum is currently closed, and isn't scheduled to reopen until 2025 (?).

You probably still *have* to go see Carthage if you're in Tunis, so save yourself some time and hit the Baths of Antoninus. There's at least a bit of explaination there, and it's fun to scramble around a bit in the ruins.

Added by grajohnt

cisterns-of-la-malga.description:
Far and away the most 'infrastructure-y' part of the ruins of Carthage, these are interesting for their size and scope, if not their beauty.

The cisterns are in pretty good shape, with one that has clearly undergone some modern restoration work. However, the aqueduct itself is very much in ruins, and it takes some imagination to see what it might have looked like.

There is no interpretation/explanation here, so read up in advance!

Worth a quick stop, but that's about it.
cisterns-of-la-malga.name: Cisterns of La Malga

columbia-river-maritime-museum.description: The Columbia River is one of the world's most economically important, but also has one of the most dangerous entrances. This museum is almost entirely historical, and covers interesting things like the lifeboat service. Well worth the stop.

cypress-freeway-memorial-park.description:
The Loma Prieta earthquake (1989) partially collapsed a two-level expressway that ran here. The local community, mostly impoverished Black people whose neighborhood the freeway had split, acted heroically, improvising ladders and other tools, pulling trapped drivers out of the wreckage, and administering first aid while EMTs were overloaded. This is one of very few memorials to peacetime community heroism in the world.

great-mosque-of-kairouan.description:
Fascinating mosque on its surface, just for the history, but look deeper and it's even more interesting. It is considered a masterpiece of Islamic architecture, but lacks the adornments common in later buildings. The 'uncountable' columns that hold up the vaulted ceilings are clearly reused Roman/Byzantine columns with a wild assortment of capitals and materials. Each one is a bit different in height, so they made up the difference with bricks before building the brick vaulted ceilings. There is carved Latin text (some upside-down) on the courtyard side of the minaret that clearly demonstrates the reuse of older material.

The whole courtyard is a rainwater collection system, and there are circular wells on the north end of the courtyard where you can peek down into the massive cisterns built underneath.

The little staircase in the middle of the courtyard leads to a sundial, which is also worth a look.

Worth at least half an hour to look around - more if you're really into Roman columns.

kth-r1.description:
KTH Reactor Hall
The research reactor R1 is an experimental stage today, a creative venue for meetings between different disciplines.

The Reactor Hall originally housed Sweden's first nuclear reactor, research reactor R1. It was operational between 1954 and 1970, and even though the reactor itself has long since been removed, the Reactor Hall still has an aura of research and experimentation.

Today, KTH uses the Reactor Hall as a combination of museum, culture centre, seminar room, studio, lab and more. Not least for activities with artistic university colleges in Stockholm. https://www.kth.se/en/thetale/standard-avdelning/kth-reaktorhallen-1.1135540

Allow at least an hour or so to explore the whole ruin.

northam-traincare-facility.description: Depot for South Western Railway trains. Occasional open days.
northam-traincare-facility.name: Northam Traincare Facility

novelty-automation.description: Filled with loads of brilliant hand made mechanical arcade machines made by Tim Hunkin (of 'Secret life of' fame). Go and play and marvel at the mechanisms.
novelty-automation.name: Novelty Automation

null-island.description: Approximate Location of Null Island. If you are looking for something that says it's here, it's probably actually not.
null-island.name: Null Island

oakham-treasures.description: Very weird and wonderful museum of all sorts of things. Officially "retail and farming history" but includes a large selection of painted tractor seats (yes, really), a model railway, model Shaun the Sheeps, historic packaging, haberdashery and more. Very strange, but quite fun. Wheelchair accessible.
oakham-treasures.name: Oakham Treasures

oakland-museum-of-california.description: Broad in scope, from local nature to contemporary arts. Every time I take someone here we leave wishing we had more time.
oakland-museum-of-california.name: Oakland Museum of California

ocean-star-offshore-drilling-rig-and-mus.name: Ocean Star Offshore Drilling Rig and Museum
Ocean Star Offshore Drilling Rig and Museum

old-mam-tor-road.description: Formerly the main road from Sheffield to Manchester, intended to be a gentler gradient than Winnats Pass to the south. Unfortunately, it crosses an active landslide and had to be repeatedly repaired until they gave up. You can now visit the old road on foot. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mam_Tor#Landslides
old-mam-tor-road.name: Old Mam Tor Road

ongar-00-datum-point-for-the-london-unde.description: The point at which all distances are measured from on the London Underground
ongar-00-datum-point-for-the-london-unde.name: Ongar 0.0 Datum Point for the London Underground

oregon-shakespeare-festival.description: A somewhat quixotic Shakespeare festival in a middle-of-nowhere town that slowly became one of the world's largest.
oregon-shakespeare-festival.name: Oregon Shakespeare Festival

orford-ness.description: Military test site, inc bomb test chambers and the fantastically-named Cobra Mist experimental radar station. Various remains still visible.
orford-ness.name: Orford Ness

osaka-aquarium-kaiyukan.description: The Osaka Aquarium is world-class and well worth a trip. (I mean, they have a tank with whale sharks in it!)
osaka-aquarium-kaiyukan.name: Osaka Aquarium Kaiyukan

ossuary-in-the-crypt-of-st-leonards-chur.description: One of only two ossuaries in the UK. See https://www.slhk.org/theossuary.htm
ossuary-in-the-crypt-of-st-leonards-chur.name: Ossuary in the Crypt of St Leonard's church

ouarzazate-noor-solar-power-station.description: Among the largest solar power plants in the world. Not open to casual visitors, but tours can be arranged (https://www.masen.ma/en/site-visit-request) and are apparently very interesting.
ouarzazate-noor-solar-power-station.name: Ouarzazate (Noor) Solar Power Station

paddock-standby-cabinet-war-room.description:
Occasional tours through Sub-Brit or on London Open House week. Doesn't seem to have been opened for Open House recently though.

Lots of detailed info at https://www.subbrit.org.uk/sites/paddock-standby-cabinet-war-room/
paddock-standby-cabinet-war-room.name: PADDOCK Standby Cabinet War Room

palvolgyi-cave.description: Ed: Smallish cave you can tour. Comes free with Budapest tourist card.
palvolgyi-cave.name: Palvolgyi Cave

pattersongimlin-film-site.description: The most famous video “evidence” of Sasquatch.
pattersongimlin-film-site.name: Patterson–Gimlin Film Site

pendon-museum.description: A glimpse of English rural life around 1930 through extraordinary dioramas featuring models of railways, villages and landscapes.
pendon-museum.name: Pendon Museum

pentrich-revolution-trail.description:
Trail around sites involved in the Pentrich Revolution - an armed uprising that took place in 1817.

Walking guide: https://info.ambervalley.gov.uk/docarc/docviewer.aspx?docGuid=3514f6233182445c93afa6edca209e46
pentrich-revolution-trail.name: Pentrich Revolution Trail

petite-ceinture.description:
Abandoned circle rail line in various states of development

https://www.petiteceinture-info.fr/
petite-ceinture.name: Petite Ceinture

phone-box-at-the-centre-of-great-britain.description:
Phone box with a plaque in it marking the geographic centre of Great Britain.

See https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/5031162 and https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/5031165
phone-box-at-the-centre-of-great-britain.name: Phone box at the centre of Great Britain

pinnacles-national-park.description:
Pinnacles is one of the main sites of the successful California condor recovery program, which has brought them back from just a few dozen individuals. The interpretive material on-site is unfortunately fairly scant.

A Pinnacles trip requires planning: Avoid busy times (like long weekends), beware of very high temperatures in summer, and bring supplies. With those caveats, the hiking is exceptionally enjoyable and spectacular. Bring binoculars to see condors and a number of other interesting birds.
pinnacles-national-park.name: Pinnacles National Park

pitlochry-dam-visitor-centre.description: Hydroelectric dam visitors centre with salmon ladder that can be viewed to see the salmon leaping up.
pitlochry-dam-visitor-centre.name: Pitlochry Dam Visitor Centre

pitt-rivers-museum.description: Pitt Rivers Museum is a museum displaying the archaeological and anthropological collections of the University of Oxford in England.
pitt-rivers-museum.name: Pitt Rivers Museum

pk-porthcurno.description:
MUSEUM OF GLOBAL COMMUNICATIONS

Many transatlantic cables land here, and there's a museum in some old landing buildings.
pk-porthcurno.name: PK Porthcurno

point-bonita-lighthouse.description: Not the most interesting of the region's lighthouses, but still pretty great, and very accessible from the inner Bay Area.
point-bonita-lighthouse.name: Point Bonita Lighthouse

point-no-point-lighthouse.description: Open only on Saturdays, but the home of the US Lighthouse Society, and a good area to walk around
point-no-point-lighthouse.name: Point No Point Lighthouse

point-reyes-lighthouse.description: Other interesting things on Point Reyes include sea lions.
point-reyes-lighthouse.name: Point Reyes Lighthouse

pontcysyllte-aqueduct.description: Nice canal basin/boat yard at one end, with a little shop for ice creams etc. One of the cottages alongside the canal is a holiday cottage which is a nice place to stay.
pontcysyllte-aqueduct.name: Pontcysyllte Aqueduct

ponte-da-arrbida.description: Ed: do a tour climbing the underside of this tall bridge.
ponte-da-arrbida.name: Ponte da Arrábida

port-museum-of-dunkirk.description: They do boat tours of the docks
port-museum-of-dunkirk.name: Port Museum of Dunkirk

portland-loo.description: Example of a heavily used Portland Loo, a distinctive kind of public toilet: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portland_Loo
portland-loo.name: Portland Loo

portmeirion-north-wales.description: Bonkers weird town, as seen in famous film The Prisoner
portmeirion-north-wales.name: Portmeirion North Wales

postojna-cave.description: Ed: Multi km cave system. Go on a mini train in to the middle and out again! It's very touristy with 100s of tourists and hour, but well recommended as a totally bizarre experience. The tours are split up so it doesn't feel too busy at any one time. Train is fun. Better to book in advance, but they seem to reserve enough capacity to serve some walk-ups. The other Vivarium wasn't worth it.
postojna-cave.name: Postojna Cave

powells-city-of-books.description: Extremely large and wonderful independent bookstore.
powells-city-of-books.name: Powell's City of Books

power-house-2-near-snoqualmie-falls.description: A power plant right next to a water fall. Worth a short trip if you're in the area, especially if you're going to see the falls anyway. You can't actually access the power house itself, but you can see the inside through windows and there's an elevated walkway that let's you see the falls from the downstream side.
power-house-2-near-snoqualmie-falls.name: Power House #2, near Snoqualmie Falls

prelinger-library.description: Highly influential library and film archive.
prelinger-library.name: Prelinger Library

progreso-pier.description: The longest in the world by some measures. Most of its length is closed to the public except when going to or from a cruise ship docked here. Still an impressive sight from shore.
progreso-pier.name: Progreso Pier

pulgas-water-temple.description: 1930s structure and viewing pond to celebrate the completion of the Hetch Hetchy water system supplying San Francisco.
pulgas-water-temple.name: Pulgas Water Temple

purton-ship-graveyard.description: A 'graveyard' of barges beached to shore up the banks of the Gloucester and Sharpness Canal alongside the River Severn.
purton-ship-graveyard.name: Purton Ship Graveyard

puzzling-world.description: A museum of optical illusions, an impossible leaning tower and an incredible 2 level great maze with 1.5km of passages.
puzzling-world.name: Puzzling World

rafusaf-menwith-hill.description:
RAF/USAF listening station. Heavily linked with GCHQ and the Echelon programme. No public access, but good views of the radomes from the surrounding area. Beware of photography.

See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RAF_Menwith_Hill
rafusaf-menwith-hill.name: RAF/USAF Menwith Hill

rahmi-ko-mzesi.description:
This is an absolute *must see* museum in Istanbul. Primarily a transportation museum, and has an extensive collection of cars, train cars, a submarine, airplanes, and naval paraphenalia. There's also an entire hall of scientific instruments, and exhibits devoted to household appliances.

Worth a good half-day. A bit off the beaten track, but there are direct ferries from the old city, although these can be tricky to track down.

-added by jt
rahmi-ko-mzesi.name: Rahmi Koç Müzesi

railway-museum.description: Ed: By far the cooler bit is that surrounding the museum are the wrecks of a load of old trains you can just wander around.
railway-museum.name: Railway Museum

railworld-wildlife-haven.description: The only place to go if you want to see a Tracked Hovercraft (aka Hovertrain)
railworld-wildlife-haven.name: Railworld Wildlife Haven

ramsgate-hoverport-remains.description: Only the tarmac left - so probably not worth visiting unless you're in the area anyway
ramsgate-hoverport-remains.name: Ramsgate Hoverport Remains

randalls-and-ward-islands.description: Great vantage points under the Triborough and Hell Gate bridges
randalls-and-ward-islands.name: Randalls and Ward Islands

rc-harris-water-treatment-plant.description: Art-deco water treatment plant on the waterfront.  Open to the public only once a year during Doors Open, but the outside is still nice if you're at the nearby beach.
rc-harris-water-treatment-plant.name: R.C. Harris Water Treatment Plant

rdhuset-t-bana.description: All the blue line stations are carved out of the bedrock and decorated by local artists
rdhuset-t-bana.name: Rådhuset T-bana

red-rock-island.description: Technically part of three counties and two cities. Privately owned. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Rock_Island
red-rock-island.name: Red Rock Island

reigate-caves.description: Interesting former sand mines which have had many uses (known and unknown) over the years.
reigate-caves.name: Reigate Caves

rem-restaurant-bar-rooftop.description: A restaurant & bar on a former oil rig platform
rem-restaurant-bar-rooftop.name: REM - Restaurant | Bar | Rooftop

remains-of-mulberry-harbours-in-rigg-bay.description: Remains of some of the parts of the Mulberry floating harbours used in the D-Day invasion. More details at https://mulberryharbour.info/
remains-of-mulberry-harbours-in-rigg-bay.name: Remains of Mulberry Harbours in Rigg Bay

riverside-museum.description: Transport and other things museum. Has a wall of cars that looks like they are toy cars, but they're actually real!
riverside-museum.name: Riverside Museum

rnas-culdrose-public-viewing-area.description: Used to be coach tours of the station, seem to have stopped now
rnas-culdrose-public-viewing-area.name: RNAS Culdrose Public Viewing Area

rnli-barry-island-visitors-centre-and-sh.name: RNLI Barry Island Visitors Centre and Shop

romancecar-museum.description:
The Odakyu lines operate very nice "romance car" train service out to the area just outside Mt. Fuji. Called this because instead of bench seating like most commuter trains they have very nice forward facing seating (loveseats, like the furniture) for a comfortable long journey.

This museum covers the history of the special service and rolling stock. It also has a spectacular massive diorama of the whole train line
romancecar-museum.name: Romancecar Museum

romney-hythe-dymchurch-railway.description: Narrow gauge railway (runs towards Dungeness where you can see the power station, sound mirrors and more)
romney-hythe-dymchurch-railway.name: Romney Hythe & Dymchurch Railway

romsey-signal-box.description: Lever-frame signal box and associated signals, points etc, all connected up to a simulator. Open on selected days see https://romseysignalbox.org.uk/
romsey-signal-box.name: Romsey Signal Box

ronald-reagan-minuteman-missile-state-hi.name: Ronald Reagan Minuteman Missile State Historic Site

roosevelt-island-tramway.description:
Aerial tramway connecting Roosevelt Island to the Upper East Side of Manhattan. Visit the awesome 1970's architecture of Roosevelt Island

https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roosevelt_Island_Tramway
roosevelt-island-tramway.name: Roosevelt Island Tramway

roosevelt-island-tramway-island-station.description:
Aerial tramway connecting Roosevelt Island to the Upper East Side of Manhattan. Visit the awesome 1970's architecture of Roosevelt Island

https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roosevelt_Island_Tramway
roosevelt-island-tramway-island-station.name: Roosevelt Island Tramway - Island station

rosie-the-riveter-national-historical-pa.name: Rosie the Riveter National Historical Park

royal-air-force-museum-midlands2.description: The RAF museum-V bombers hanging from the roof, atomic bombs, cold war propaganda and all sorts. And its close to a village called Tong Havana!
royal-air-force-museum-midlands2.name: Royal Air Force Museum Midlands

royal-college-of-music-museum.description: Earliest known guitar, early keyboard instruments, portraits and more.
royal-college-of-music-museum.name: Royal College of Music Museum

royal-mills.description:
Walk around these mills in Ancoats and you understand what the Prussian architect Friedrich Karl Schinkel felt in 1825, when he marvelled: "the enormous factory buildings are seven to eight storeys high...where three years ago there were only meadows"
http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/history/victorian/Victorian3.html
royal-mills.name: Royal Mills

royal-navy-fleet-air-arm-museum.name: Royal Navy Fleet Air Arm Museum

royal-victoria-country-park-and-historic.description:
Country Park on the site of old hospital used in WW1 by Florence Nightingale. Most of hospital burnt down in the 1960s. Chapel is left with a museum in it, plus tower access sometimes.

Miniature railway also there.
royal-victoria-country-park-and-historic.name: Royal Victoria Country Park and Historic Hospital

ruby-beach.description: Representative of many similar beaches on this stretch of coast. Old-growth temperate rainforest grows up to the beach, which is broad (at low tide) and mostly sandy, with huge driftwood. A significant fraction of visible litter is from China and Japan and has crossed the Pacific over several years.
ruby-beach.name: Ruby Beach

ruins-of-raf-stoney-cross.description: Ruins of old WW2 airfield in the New Forest. Lots of bits of taxiways and runways available (look on satellite view), old lighting structures etc. The main runway is now the suspiciously straight road. Lots of pleasant New Forest scenery, plus ice cream vans, and local ponds/lakes.
ruins-of-raf-stoney-cross.name: Ruins of RAF Stoney Cross

samphire-hoe-country-park.description: Made out of spoil from construction of the Channel Tunnel! Can see some tunnel infra here.
samphire-hoe-country-park.name: Samphire Hoe Country Park

san-andreas-fault.description: This stretch of 1, between Pt Reyes Station and Woodville, runs almost exactly along the San Andreas Fault. At any given moment the left wheels of your car might be on the Pacific Plate and the right wheels on the North American Plane.
san-andreas-fault.name: San Andreas Fault

san-andreas-fault-observatory-at-depth.name: San Andreas Fault Observatory at Depth

san-andreas-fault-plaque.description:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Andreas_Fault#/media/File:San_Andreas_Fault_San_Mateo.jpg

The fault is named after the valley, not the other way around. (At the time of its identification, geologists did not yet understand how long it was; if they had, presumably it would have been named something like the California Coastal Fault.)
san-andreas-fault-plaque.name: San Andreas Fault plaque

san-diego-zoo.description: One of the first zoos to make a real effort to keep animals in humane, pseudo-natural conditions and not as if they were mere museum pieces.
san-diego-zoo.name: San Diego Zoo

san-francisco-cable-car-museum.description: Working plant that pulls the cable cars with good museum exhibits.  Take the cable car to get here!
san-francisco-cable-car-museum.name: San Francisco Cable Car Museum

san-francisco-city-hall.description:
Possible to sometimes tour the main domed ceiling?

https://twitter.com/djbaskin/status/1637607989497700352
san-francisco-city-hall.name: San Francisco City Hall

san-francisco-railway-museum.description: Tiny but central and therefore worth popping in to. It's also near a stop on the F Market streetcar line, which runs a variety of PCCs and international vintage trams.
san-francisco-railway-museum.name: San Francisco Railway Museum

san-joaquin-river-national-wildlife-refu.description: One of very few remaining spots in the Central Valley that gives a reasonable impression of what the pre-Columbian landscape looked like.
san-joaquin-river-national-wildlife-refu.name: San Joaquin River National Wildlife Refuge

san-juan-island-nhp-english-camp-visitor.description: One of two sites documenting the Pig War, a US/UK border dispute.
san-juan-island-nhp-english-camp-visitor.name: San Juan Island NHP, English Camp Visitor Center

san-pablo-dam.description: Easily accessible example of a type of reservoir dam common in the region.
san-pablo-dam.name: San Pablo Dam

santiago-peak.description: Based on one GIS analysis, this is the point in the US from which you can see the largest amount of urbanized land.
santiago-peak.name: Santiago Peak

satellite-control-of-network.description: For the fans of huge parabolic dishes.
satellite-control-of-network.name: Satellite Control Of Network

scapa-flow-museum.description: Lots of interesting WW2 naval stuff - they even have anti-submarine netting in the car park.
scapa-flow-museum.name: Scapa Flow Museum

schiehallion.description: A fantastic easy hill walk with spectacular views. Nerdy significance: a groundbreaking 1774 experiment to estimate Newton's Gravitational constant G by measuring the deflection of a pendulum by the mass of the mountain to provide an estimate of the mean density of the Earth. There's some signage near the bottom about the experiment.
schiehallion.name: Schiehallion

science-and-industry-museum.description: Lots of functioning steam engines in the Power Hall.
science-and-industry-museum.name: Science and Industry Museum

science-oxford-centre.description: Hands on science for nerdy kids (and their nerdy carers).
science-oxford-centre.name: Science Oxford Centre

scott-russell-aqueduct.description: Location of the first sighting of a 'soliton wave' - see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soliton
scott-russell-aqueduct.name: Scott Russell Aqueduct

sea-life-kelly-tarltons-aquarium.description:
The Antarctic Encounter is home to New Zealand's only sub-Antarctic penguins, offering a rare opportunity to see the magnificent birds up close in their icy domain. A unique snowcat ride brings you within arms length of the 80-strong colony of King and Gentoo penguins to watch their playful antics on the snow and their elegant flight underwater.

A walkthrough replica of Captain Robert Falcon Scott's Antarctic hut (established back in 1911), complete with authentic memorabilia offers a glimpse at what it was like to live 100 years ago in the coldest place on Earth."
sea-life-kelly-tarltons-aquarium.name: SEA LIFE Kelly Tarlton's Aquarium

seafield-waste-water-treatment-works.description: Has opened on Doors Open Day in the past https://www.scottishwater.co.uk/About-Us/News-and-Views/2022/10/041022-Seafield-Doors-Open-Day
seafield-waste-water-treatment-works.name: Seafield waste water treatment works

seaford-museum-of-local-history.description: Museum in Martello Tower No.74 aka The Tardis - what a museum ought to be like - full of all kinds of nerdy junk: old computers, old radios, all sorts...
seaford-museum-of-local-history.name: Seaford Museum of Local History

secret-junction-135-of-m4.description: Junction for RAF Welford munitions storage facility. See https://www.secret-bases.co.uk/secret4.htm#welford
secret-junction-135-of-m4.name: Secret Junction 13.5 of M4

sewer-tour-mann-tour.description: Ed: Tour a section of the Vienna sewers, as seen in the 3rd Mann film.
sewer-tour-mann-tour.name: Sewer tour - Mann Tour

sf-bay-ferry.description: Excellent views under the Bay Bridge, past the Port of Oakland, etc., depending on route. Subsidized as a disaster preparedness program in order to provide emergency transport in case bridges are damaged in a major earthquake. Easily the most pleasant way to cross the Bay.
sf-bay-ferry.name: SF Bay Ferry

sfo-museum-louis-a-turpen-aviation-museu.description: The SFO Museum is a fully accredited museum whose grounds also happen to serve as the world's 24th largest airport by passenger count. Even if you can't visit the museum proper, look out for small displays in the terminals.
sfo-museum-louis-a-turpen-aviation-museu.name: SFO Museum Louis A. Turpen Aviation Museum and Library

sheldon-country-park-birmingham-airport-.description: Seats at the end of the runway of Birmingham Airport. Park at Marston Green Railway Station, take a picnic and watch the planes.
sheldon-country-park-birmingham-airport-.name: Sheldon Country Park - Birmingham Airport viewing area

shinjuku-golden-gai.description: 50+ microscopic bars rammed into 5 tiny alleys across multiple floors. Note that some of the bars are locals only and they won't let you in. Super fun. Expect to be in a bar the size of a small caravan with four seats where nobody speaks English.
shinjuku-golden-gai.name: Shinjuku Golden Gai

shoreham-airport.description:
Working airport, with museum and exhibits. Some special open days.

https://flybrighton.com/
shoreham-airport.name: Shoreham Airport

shoreham-cement-works.description:
Closed to public and not in use anymore, but the site is huge. 

https://www.bcd-urbex.com/shoreham-cement-works-west-sussex/

https://www.shorehambysea.com/chalk-history-shoreham-beeding-cement-works/
shoreham-cement-works.name: Shoreham Cement works

shoreham-power-station.description:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoreham_Power_Station

The best way to get to it, is to cross the locks.  You'll often catch some of the huge port ships moving timber, shingle and cement in and out of the port
shoreham-power-station.name: Shoreham Power Station

shoreline-traces-of-lake-missoula.description: Which periodically flooded huge areas of the Pacific Northwest: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glacial_Lake_Missoula
shoreline-traces-of-lake-missoula.name: Shoreline traces of Lake Missoula

shortest-piece-of-standard-gauge-track.description: The shortest extant piece of standard gauge track, in the middle of a roundabout in Basingstoke.
shortest-piece-of-standard-gauge-track.name: Shortest piece of standard gauge track

shuttleworth-collection.description: Vintage cars and aeroplanes and more
shuttleworth-collection.name: Shuttleworth Collection

silbury-hill.description:
The largest artificial mound in Europe, mysterious Silbury Hill compares in height and volume to the roughly contemporary Egyptian pyramids. Probably completed in around 2400 BC, it apparently contains no burial. Though clearly important in itself, its purpose and significance remain unknown.

https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/silbury-hill/
silbury-hill.name: Silbury Hill

singing-ringing-tree.description: The Singing Ringing Tree is a wind powered sound sculpture resembling a tree set in the landscape of the Pennine hill range overlooking Burnley, in Lancashire, England.
singing-ringing-tree.name: Singing Ringing Tree

sinking-of-the-valencia.description: The region's most deadly shipwreck, in 1906: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Valencia#Final_voyage
sinking-of-the-valencia.name: Sinking of the “Valencia”

sir-john-soanes-museum.description: Discover the extraordinary house and museum of Sir John Soane, one of the greatest English architects, who built and lived in it two centuries ago. The museum has been kept as it was at the time of his death in 1837, and displays his vast collection of antiquities, furniture, sculptures, architectural models and paintings.
sir-john-soanes-museum.name: Sir John Soane's Museum

site-of-morning-mist-rock-island-bend-fr.description: A photo sometimes credited with helping turn an election and saving the river from a large dam: https://urth.co/magazine/the-photo-that-saved-the-franklin-river
site-of-morning-mist-rock-island-bend-fr.name: Site of “Morning Mist, Rock Island Bend, Franklin River”

skaggs-island-circularly-disposed-antenn.name: Skaggs Island Circularly Disposed Antenna Array (CDAA)

skye-ferry.description:
The last manually operated steel turntable ferry in the world.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MV_Glenachulish
skye-ferry.name: Skye Ferry

skyterrace.description: Outside and landside viewpoint for plane spotting, but unfortunately it does require a quick security screening. There's also an airside viewpoint at the end of Terminal G (on Google Maps as "SFO Outdoor Terrace").
skyterrace.name: SkyTerrace

sl-1-site.description: An early (1961) nuclear accident that was very influential on US government thinking about nuclear safety: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SL-1
sl-1-site.name: SL-1 site

slac-national-accelerator-laboratory.description: Visible from I-280 and possibly on incoming flights to San Francisco and San Jose
slac-national-accelerator-laboratory.name: SLAC National Accelerator Laboratory

smedley-street-ww2-resistance-hq.description: Between 1939 to 1945, Burton House, a building on Smedley Street Matlock, played an undercover role during the war as the headquarters for Matlock's Secret Army. There is a blue plaque commemorating this.
smedley-street-ww2-resistance-hq.name: Smedley Street WW2 Resistance HQ

smith-teamaker.description: Final tea project of the man who founded and sold Stash, then founded and sold Tazo: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steven_Smith_(teamaker)
smith-teamaker.name: Smith Teamaker

smithsonian-national-air-and-space-museu.name: Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum

snowdon-mountain-railway-ticket-office.description: Rack and pinion mountain railway https://snowdonrailway.co.uk/
snowdon-mountain-railway-ticket-office.name: Snowdon Mountain Railway ticket office

solent-sky.description: Aviation museum. Has a massive sea plane you can go inside - including into the cockpit if you ask nicely.
solent-sky.name: Solent Sky

solheimasandur-plane-wreck.description: Instagram famous wreck of a plane. Cool to visit if you can spare the time. At least an hour walk each way.
solheimasandur-plane-wreck.name: Solheimasandur Plane Wreck

sousse-archaeological-museum.description:
A museum and ancient structure in one!

This museum is part of the UNESCO-listed Sousse Medina, and is built into the Sousse Kasbah in a very tasteful and architecturally interesting way.

It is mostly devoted to Roman/Byzantine mosaics, and the Byzantine baptismal font is worth a visit alone.

Sadly, you can't see much of the kasbah itself, rather than admiring it from the outside (it's beautifully lit at night, with a functioning lighthouse). If you want to explore a similar structure, head to the Sousse Ribat on the other side of the medina. (The mosque isn't worth a visit, sadly).

Allow an hour or two for a visit. The parking is free, and at the time of writing (2023) was also the best place for overnight parking for the medina.

Added by grajohnt

star-wars-mos-espa.description:
You will never find a more wretch hive of touts and degraded Hollywood sets.

Look, I get it, you're in Tunisia, and you want to see Star Wars stuff. If you're in Touzeur, it's pretty easy to visit this spot, and hopefully it will get it out of your system.

Absolutely filled with touts offering camel tours and 4-wheeler excursions across the dunes, plus a smattering of shops with the same stuff you can find anywhere else.

You can walk around in the ruins of the Berber village and see some of the set additions made for Star Wars. These were clearly just barely good enough to work for a set, and are starting to get somewhat decrepit.

The drive out there is across the desert on a road that must be regularly 'plowed' to remove blowing sand. You will spend more time getting there than you do visiting, so enjoy this part!

wikchsawa-superstition-mountains.description:
Beautiful mountains, but notoriously dangerous. The heat is often extreme, the trails are exposed and exhausting (people forget they're at elevation when they're hot!), and the brush is deceptively thick, making it easy to get lost and take a step off a cliff. A truly alarming number of hikers have died here, and their remains often go unfound in the dense scrub and many tiny canyons.

Also the site of the folkloric lost Dutchman's gold (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lost_Dutchman%27s_Gold_Mine), one of the more interesting and culturally important buried treasure stories of the West. In some versions, it's a small but very rich gold seam; in others, it's a cache of conquistador-looted gold hidden in a rock cleft by Apaches; presumably some people think it's aliens. Over the last century or more, large numbers of treasure hunters have, unsurprisingly, died while offtrail in this exceptionally dangerous landscape. This has only fed the legends of curses and increased the perceived value of the gold. There are entire (fairly entertaining) books just about the histories of the various expeditions.

Arizona State Parks advises you to plan your hike carefully, particularly as regards your water supply, and to stay strictly on marked trails. This is good advice.
